Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} on
medium heat.

Add the @egg noodle nest{2} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking
together.

== Preparation ==

Trim the @pak choi{1}, then cut into roughly 2cm pieces.

Drain the @king prawns{225%g} and pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1} (stalks and all). Zest and halve the
@lime{1/2}.

Crush the @salted peanuts{25%g} in the unopened sachet using a #rolling pin{}.

== Laksa ==

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large saucepan on medium-high heat.

Add the @yellow Thai style paste{45%g} and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and @water{300%ml}.

Bring to a boil, then lower the heat and stir in the @peanut butter{30%g} until
well combined.

Add the prawns, @mangetout{80%g} and pak choi to your laksa.

Stir well and cook until the prawns are cooked and veg is tender, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're
> cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine the coriander, lime zest, peanuts,
@olive oil{1.5%tbsp} and a squeeze of lime juice. Set aside.

== Assembly ==

Once the prawns are cooked, stir the cooked noodles into the laksa and heat
through until piping hot, ~{1%minute}. Add a splash of water if it's a little
too thick.

Stir through the @soy sauce{15%ml} and a good squeeze of lime juice.

Taste and season with @ground black pepper{} and more lime juice if you like.

== Serving ==

Share your prawn laksa between your #bowls{} and drizzle over the parsley pesto.

Cut any remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside. Enjoy!